WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Hello everybody, my name is Ryan Johnson, and I'm a data science advisor here at Posit.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Welcome to this month's Enterprise Community Meetup, where we'll discuss another end-to-end data science workflow using Posit Team.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Just as a reminder, this is a recurring event that occurs on the last Wednesday of every month,

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:25.000
and we hope it'll serve as a good primer for those that are brand new to Posit Team,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:30.000
but also help current Posit Team users become more familiar with our tools.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Now with the holiday season upon us, there's no better way to express your holiday spirit

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
than by sharing the gift of a beautifully crafted, organized data science workflow.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:48.000
So with that in mind, and during today's demo, we're going to discuss tools and techniques within Posit's toolchain

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.000
specifically designed for sharing and collaborating with others.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:01.000
So to kick things off, I first want to make sure everyone here has a solid high-level understanding of Posit Team.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
So Posit Team, it's a bundled offering of our three professional tools.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
We have Posit Workbench, Posit Connect, and Posit Package Manager.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
And if we start right up here at the top with your data scientists, they're going to be creating insights,

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.000
so writing code within Posit Workbench, and they can choose whichever IDE they want.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.000
It can be RStudio, JupyterLab, Jupyter Notebook, or VS Code.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:28.000
And they can also program in whatever language they want.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:35.000
So for your R developers, maybe they're creating things like Shiny applications, or R Markdown, or Cordo documents.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:43.000
And for your Python developers, maybe they're creating Jupyter Notebooks, or FastAPI, Streamlit, Shiny, Vetiver, and the list goes on.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
But it doesn't do your developers any good if they can't share this content with the people that need to see it.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And that's the whole purpose of Posit Connect.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:57.000
This is our professional publishing platform, so it gives a home for all this content your data scientists are creating,

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
so that they can easily share them with the people that need to see them.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:06.000
And that could be, you know, coworkers, it could be decision makers at your company,

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.000
or maybe you just want to share it with friends and family.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:14.000
And then our last tool is Posit Package Manager, which does exactly as its name implies.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:19.000
It helps control all those amazing open source R and Python packages your team uses.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
It also gives a home to any internally developed R and Python packages.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
We also just released some really cool new features within Package Manager,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.000
so you can actually control access over which packages your team can use.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.000
Now, before we get into the actual demo, I want to take a moment to talk about, you know,

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:43.000
why does Posit care so much about open source data science?

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
In the list I'm going to present, it's not an exhaustive list,

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.000
but I did want to highlight a few points why Posit is so invested in open source data science,

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:56.000
especially in the context of sharing and collaborating.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:02.000
First, open source data science is free, meaning if you want to share your workflow with someone else,

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
there is no requirement to purchase any software.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:10.000
All the components needed to run the workflow are completely free of charge.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Second, open source data science, it promotes transparency.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
Now, when you share a workflow with someone, they will know everything,

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:24.000
and I mean everything, that went into your analyses because they have access to your source code.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000
There's no proprietary or black box analyses that are hidden from your collaborators.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And finally, open source data science allows teams to easily collaborate with specific people,

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
but also with the greater data science community.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
I'm sure many folks listening to this webinar right now have likely had a data science question

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
and posted it to a public forum and hopefully got a response from the community.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.000
This is the type of data science learning and support that Posit wants to encourage.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:00.000
So what options exist today to collaborate and share content using Posit's tools?

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:06.000
Well, the first way is to share your source code, and that's where version control comes into play.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:13.000
So many of the tools that we create here at Posit, including the various IDEs included in Posit Workbench,

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:18.000
they have integrations to make working with version control, including Git, a breeze.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:25.000
Version control and repository hosting services like GitHub, or maybe your team uses Bitbucket,

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:30.000
are some of the most important tools for data science collaboration.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.000
We also have some cool features built into Posit team that can assist with data science collaboration,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
including project sharing and Git back deployment.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:47.000
So project sharing, this is a feature in Posit Workbench and allows for users to work together on RStudio projects.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:53.000
You can even do live code editing with this feature, which we'll demonstrate a little bit later on.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Finally, we'll finish our workflow today by demonstrating Git back deployment within Posit Connect,

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:06.000
which can be used to directly deploy content to Posit Connect from a Git repository.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:12.000
So to go over today's workflow, we are first going to start by creating a new repository on GitHub,

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.000
which will be the home base, so to speak, for our collaborative data science project.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.000
We'll then pull the repository into Posit Workbench as an RStudio project.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
For this simple workflow, we're going to be creating a Shiny application in R,

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:35.000
and we'll show you how more than one user can collaborate on the same piece of code using version control as well as project sharing.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:43.000
And I'll be showing version control features in both RStudio as well as Visual Studio Code running within Posit Workbench.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Finally, we'll show you how to publish the collaborative Shiny application hosted on GitHub to Posit Connect using Git back deployment.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:00.000
So to kick off this workflow, here I am within my GitHub homepage, and I'm going to start a brand new repository.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:06.000
So in the top right corner, you'll see this green new button. Go ahead and click on this.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:11.000
I'm going to choose me as the owner, and I'm just going to give this repository a random name.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:15.000
I'll just call it Test Repo 123.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:20.000
For the description, I'll just say this is a test repo.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
We'll make this public, and I'll go ahead and add a readme.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:27.000
And then I'll hit create repository.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.000
