if you look over here in the top right-hand side,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.000
there's a tab up here in the top right called Git.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
And this is going to show you all the Git integrations

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:00.000
within the RStudio IDE.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:04.000
And currently we see a lot of question marks right now.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
So the first file is this gitignore file.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
This was actually added by RStudio when we created this project,

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:14.000
as well as this testrepo123.rproj file,

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
which is always created in the home directory of a project,

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:19.000
an RStudio project.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
And then we also have this testapp directory.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
So I come back to my projects directory, which is right here.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:30.000
And inside of it is going to be that Shiny application.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
Now, currently we see all these question marks.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:36.000
And that's because Git, version control, it sees these files

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
but doesn't really know what to do with them.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
Should it ignore them? Should it track them?

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:44.000
But we want to go ahead and have Git track these files

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
so that we can push them up to GitHub.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:51.000
So to kick off that process, the first thing we're going to do

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
is stage all these files.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.000
And I like to think of it just like staging for a play.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:57.000
So while the curtains are still closed,

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:00.000
you want to make sure everything's set up in the right place,

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:04.000
it's staged and ready to go for when those curtains open.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
So let's go ahead and stage these three objects.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.000
So I'll click the bottom one, the middle one,

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:12.000
and the top one right here.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
So once we have these all staged,

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:18.000
we're going to go ahead and make a local commit to version control.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
And if you see right here, this toolbar,

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.000
it provides a lot of helpful operations for Git

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
right here within the RStudio IDE.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:30.000
So you don't necessarily have to use the terminal or the command line.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
So I'm going to select this commit box.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:34.000
And it's going to open up a window here,

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:37.000
which I'm going to adjust.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.000
And let's just go ahead and explore this for a second.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:41.000
So over here in the top left corner,

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:44.000
this is the same window that we were seeing within the RStudio IDE,

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
the three files.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
And now since they're staged, you can see this little A.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
That corresponds to being added.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
So these have been added to version control,

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
they're staged, they're ready to go.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:58.000
And down here at the bottom, you can see any differences.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
Now, every single one of these files

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
is completely new to version control,

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
which is why everything's showing up in green.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:08.000
But if you were to make any edits or remove any lines,

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
you might see some red lines in here as well,

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:13.000
corresponding to things that were deleted.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:16.000
So if you're happy with all these changes, which we are,

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
we have this new shiny application

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
that we worked on collaboratively with Publisher 2.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:24.000
Let's go ahead and commit this locally to version control.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.000
We have to add a commit message here.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
Now, this is a bit of an art form

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
because you want to make these commit messages,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:34.000
as informative as possible, but also pretty short.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:38.000
So I'm just going to say, create shiny app.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:40.000
And that's pretty much it.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
I'll hit commit.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
You'll see this pop-up window,

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
which shows you some of the git commands

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:47.000
that are running in the background,

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
along with its output.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
So if I close this window,

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:54.000
you can now see the git window over here is now empty,

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:57.000
but we see this little kind of information flag,

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:59.000
letting us know that our branch is ahead of origin main

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
by one commit.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:03.000
And what that is basically telling us

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:06.000
is that our GitHub repository, hosted up in GitHub,

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:10.000
we are actually one commit ahead of what's on GitHub.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:13.000
So if we're ready to push these changes

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:14.000
up to our GitHub repository,

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:17.000
we can again use the RStudio IDE to help us out here

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:21.000
by simply clicking this push button.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
Now, you may have to set up your git

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
and GitHub credentials beforehand.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
This is something I did before this workshop,

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:30.000
just to make sure that my instance of RStudio here

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:34.000
can talk to GitHub and that it knows who I am

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
and I have the credentials to make these pushes.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
So now that we've pushed those changes,

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:41.000
let me switch back over to my GitHub repository

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:44.000
and let me refresh my page.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.000
And so here's the current state of our GitHub repository.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:50.000
We have that readme file, which we originally created.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
Here's that rproj and gitignore files

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:55.000
that RStudio automatically added for us.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:56.000
And here's our test app.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
Here's that Shiny application we're working on.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:01.000
I can click into it, click on the app.r file

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:06.000
and see all of the code.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.000
So now that we have the Shiny application on GitHub,

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.000
it is primed for collaboration.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.000
So let's say, for example, that publisher two

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:18.000
wanted to pull in this GitHub repository

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
and do some changes to their Shiny application,

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:23.000
which we're going to demonstrate right now.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.000
So here's the current state, again, of our GitHub repository.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:29.000
Let me go ahead and re-grab the URL.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:33.000
And then I'm going to drag in publisher two.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:37.000
And I'll try to make my screen a little bit nicer to see here.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.000
All right.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:41.000
So I'm going to make some changes

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:43.000
to that Shiny application as publisher two,

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.000
because, again, I'm a collaborator.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.000
I want to work alongside publisher one

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
to develop the Shiny application.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
Now, we could do this in RStudio,

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
but let me just go ahead and show you

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:56.000
how someone might do it within Visual Studio Code

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.000
running within Posit Workbench.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.000
So I'm going to open up another session,

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:02.000
because you can have multiple sessions

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:04.000
running within Posit Workbench.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
And I'm going to select Visual Studio Code

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:17.000
and hit Start Session.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:18.000
All right.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
So here we are within Visual Studio Code,

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.000
and it's pretty much a blank environment.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:25.000
If I click on my File Explorer over here,

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:28.000
it's letting me know no folder has been opened.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
And if we look along the left-hand side,

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:33.000
you'll notice there's actually a source control icon.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:34.000
So we can click on this.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:37.000
And let's go ahead and clone in that repository

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.000
that I just copied the URL for.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:43.000
So I'll click Clone Repository and paste in the URL.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:48.000
And I'm going to place it right here in my home directory.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.000
Let's go ahead and open it up.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:53.000
And now you can see within that test repo,

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:56.000
one, two, three, and here's my test app

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
with that app.r file being shown right here.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:02.000
And again, this is all running within VS Code.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
So let's say, again, as Publisher 2,

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
I want to make some changes.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.000
I'm not going to make any dramatic changes here.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:12.000
I'm just going to scroll down to, let's see, line 29.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
You can see here's the title of this dashboard,

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.000
Penguin's Dashboard.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.000
Let's make that a little bit more informative.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:22.000
Let's say Palmer Penguins Dashboard

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:25.000
because that's the dataset that we're going to be using.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.000
So we're just going to add Palmer here.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:28.000
I'll hit Save.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.000
And you'll notice there's this little one icon

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:31.000
over here in the source control.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
So let's go ahead and click on that.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:36.000
And you'll notice that there's been a change here

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:38.000
within this app.r file.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
So let's go through some of the same steps

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:43.000
we just did within RStudio.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:44.000
So the first thing we need to do

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:46.000
is we want to stage this change.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:50.000
And we can do that by clicking this little plus icon.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:51.000
And once it's been staged,

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.000
we want to add a commit message.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:56.000
And I'm just going to make it nice, short, and sweet.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:59.000
So I'll say change app title.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:02.000
And we'll hit commit.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
And once those changes have been committed,

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.000
again, locally here within VS Code,

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:08.000
running on Positive Workbench,

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:12.000
we can then push those changes up to GitHub.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.000
So again, we can just click on the sync changes.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:19.000
And that should push everything up to our GitHub repository.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.000
All right, so now that that's done,

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:27.000
let me switch back over to my GitHub repository.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:29.000
And I'll refresh my page.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:31.000
Let's just go into application

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:35.000
and make sure that change is there.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:36.000
So we'll scroll down here.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:41.000
And now you can see on line 29, Palmer Penguins dashboard.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:44.000
Now I'm going to switch back over to Publisher 1 here.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.000
Because again, now I have a change in my GitHub repository

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:51.000
that's not currently reflected within my local code

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:52.000
here as Publisher 1.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:56.000
You can still see title is the old just Penguins dashboard.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:00.000
So now would be a great time to pull in those changes

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.000
from that GitHub repository,

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:04.000
those changes made by Publisher 2.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
And to do that, again, within the RStudio IDE,

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:09.000
we have nice, easy features to do this.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:10.000
We already pushed before.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:12.000
Let's go ahead and pull.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:15.000
And once we do that, you can see all the output here

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:17.000
from running the pull command.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.000
And now if we scroll down in our source code here,

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
Palmer has been added to the title.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:27.000
So again, that's how you can work collaboratively

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:30.000
with version control using whatever IDs you want

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:34.000
with whomever you want.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:37.000
Okay, so we've shown you a few different things now

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:39.000
which are helpful for collaborating

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.000
and sharing data science workflows with others.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:45.000
But now we have this great, shiny application

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:46.000
over here on the left-hand side

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:49.000
that's been worked on by two separate developers.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:53.000
And ultimately, we want to be able to share this application

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.000
with whoever needs to see it.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:58.000
And that's where PositConnect comes into play.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:25:59.000
So we're going to go ahead and show you

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:03.000
how to publish this application to PositConnect.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:06.000
Now, here within the RStudio IDE,

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
you can actually implement something known

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:09.000
as push-button deployment.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:12.000
And we showed this in some of our previous workflows.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:15.000
Here's that little blue icon at the top of your screen

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:17.000
which you can easily push.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:21.000
And I could manually publish this to PositConnect.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:22.000
And this is a great option,

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:25.000
especially if you just want to quickly share

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:26.000
an application with somebody

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:30.000
or any piece of content that can be hosted on Connect.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
However, if I publish this to Connect

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.000
and then I come back to my source code

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:35.000
and I make a change,

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:39.000
I'm going to have to click the button again and republish.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:42.000
So it's a bit of a manual process.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:43.000
So what we're going to show you here

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:46.000
is something called get-back deployment.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:49.000
So instead of publishing it directly from the RStudio IDE,

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:51.000
we're actually just going to have PositConnect

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:54.000
look at our GitHub repository.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:58.000
And if it ever detects a change in that GitHub repository,

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:00.000
so a commit in that GitHub repository,

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:03.000
it can automatically rebuild that content for us.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:07.000
So to kick off the get-back deployment process,

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:10.000
we have a few things we need to do to get started.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
So I'm going to go ahead and just clear my console

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.000
down here in the bottom left.

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.000
And I want to go into the directory

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:17.000
that houses the content

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:21.000
that we ultimately want to be published on Connect.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:23.000
So here within that test app directory,

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:26.000
you can see we just have the single app.r file.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:30.000
And I'm actually going to set this as my working directory

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:32.000
just to make things a little bit simpler.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:37.000
Now, when we publish this application to PositConnect,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:40.000
PositConnect needs to know some information

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:43.000
about my current working environment,

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:45.000
such as what packages am I using,

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.000
what versions of those packages,

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.000
what R version am I using.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:51.000
So that information is needed by Connect

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:53.000
so that it can, you know,

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:55.000
just make sure it runs this application correctly

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:57.000
without any issues.

00:27:57.000 --> 00:27:59.000
Now, for push-button deployment, this little blue button,

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.000
a lot of that's done automatically.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:03.000
But if we're going to use GetBackDeployment,

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:05.000
we just need to provide that information,

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:07.000
and it's super easy to do it.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.000
So from within the directory

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:10.000
of the content you want to publish,

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:14.000
all you need to do is run from the rsconnect package,

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:17.000
there's a function called writeManifest.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:18.000
That's it.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:19.000
I'll hit Enter.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:21.000
It's going to capture some of my dependencies

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:24.000
using another really great package called renv.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:28.000
And then it generates this manifest.json file.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:29.000
I can click into it,

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:31.000
and we can just take a quick peek,

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:32.000
and it's pretty noisy.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:34.000
There's a lot of great information in here

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:36.000
that Connect can easily read.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:37.000
But for the most part,

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:40.000
it's just information about packages in my environment

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.000
and, like, what versions of those packages

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:43.000
and where I obtained them from.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:45.000
All the information Connect needs

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:47.000
to replicate my environment exactly as it is

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:50.000
right here within Posit Workbench.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:52.000
So now that we've created this file,

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:55.000
we want to make sure that we also include this file

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:57.000
within our GitHub repository.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:28:59.000
So let's go ahead and just show you that workflow

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:00.000
one more time.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.000
So we have this manifest.json file

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:05.000
that's been added within my Git repository

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:06.000
or within version control.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.000
Let's go ahead and stage it.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:10.000
I'm going to commit it.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:13.000
And we'll just make a quick message here

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:17.000
of add manifest file.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
And then we'll commit that up to GitHub.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:25.000
So if I come back to my GitHub repository,

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.000
we click on test app.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
I need to refresh here.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
Oh, seems like I've done something wrong here.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:33.000
Oh, yeah, I've got to push it, obviously.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
So let's go ahead and push that.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:36.000
There we go.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:38.000
So I committed it, and then I had to push it.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:40.000
Now if I refresh my page,

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:42.000
we have the app and we have the manifest file

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:45.000
right alongside of it.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:47.000
So let's go ahead and take this application

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:49.000
on my GitHub repository

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:52.000
and publish it directly from this GitHub repository.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:55.000
So I'm going to re-grab the URL for the third time.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
And I'm going to switch over to Posit Connect

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:00.000
here in this demo environment.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:02.000
So this is the home screen of Posit Connect.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:05.000
Just some example content that we have here

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:08.000
just to explore all the various pieces of content

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:11.000
you can currently host on Posit Connect.

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:12.000
But in the very top here,

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.000
you'll see this publish drop-down,

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:17.000
and I'm going to select import from Git.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:20.000
I'm going to paste in the URL

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:23.000
and I'll click next.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:26.000
And it's going to ask me what branch I want to publish from.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:29.000
Now our GitHub repository just has a single branch.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.000
It's that main branch.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:33.000
But there's actually a pretty cool workflow here

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:35.000
where you can have multiple versions

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:37.000
of a single piece of content

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:39.000
published on different branches.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:42.000
So maybe you have a production version on the main branch,

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.000
but maybe you have a development version

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:46.000
on some other branch.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
You can actually publish two pieces of content

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:51.000
from the same GitHub repository from different branches.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:53.000
But we just have one branch. That's main.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:55.000
So we'll select next.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:58.000
And then it's going to look for directories

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:01.000
where it can find that manifest.json file.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
So these are deployable directories.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:06.000
And it found one inside that test app directory.

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:08.000
And all we have to do is give our application a name.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:10.000
I'll say test app.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:12.000
We'll just keep it nice and simple.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:14.000
And then we'll hit deploy content.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.000
So at this point,

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:24.000
PositConnect is reading in that manifest file

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:27.000
and just making sure it can replicate my environment.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:30.000
And once it's done, we can click open content.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:33.000
And we'll just give it a few seconds to boot up.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:35.000
All right.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:38.000
So here's that shiny application that we've been working on.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.000
And you can actually see the title here

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:43.000
reflects that change that Publisher 2 made, Palmer.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:46.000
And it looks and it behaves just like it did

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:49.000
when it was running within Posit Workbench.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:56.000
Now, to demonstrate how powerful get back deployment is,

00:31:56.000 --> 00:32:00.000
so this application is now linked to that GitHub repository.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:02.000
And if anyone, anyone I'm collaborating with,

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:06.000
makes a change to the main branch on that GitHub repository,

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:08.000
it'll automatically be reflected here

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.000
within deployed content on PositConnect.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:13.000
So it'll automatically stay updated.

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.000
So let me actually go ahead and show you that workflow quick.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:20.000
I'm going to come back here to my environment, Publisher 1.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.000
But anyone can do this, Publisher 2

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:25.000
or anyone else that's working on this GitHub repository

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.000
and has access to that main branch.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:30.000
Let's go ahead and make another change to the title.

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:33.000
So I have PalmerPenguinsDashboard.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:35.000
And I'm just going to add a dash.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
No, I'm going to add a smiley face.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:41.000
There we go. Kind of silly, but another change.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.000
We'll hit Save.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:46.000
Now you can see in the Git tab, we have modified this file.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:48.000
So let's go ahead and stage it.

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:50.000
I'm going to commit it locally.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:54.000
And I'll say add smiley face to title.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:57.000
And then we'll commit this locally

00:32:57.000 --> 00:32:59.000
and then push it up to GitHub.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:04.000
So now if I switch back over to my GitHub repository,

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:05.000
let's just check the application

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:08.000
and make sure that change is reflected.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:11.000
So you can see the smiley face right here on line 29.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:14.000
Now I'm going to switch back over to PositConnect.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.000
I'm going to refresh my page here.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:19.000
And you'll notice that the smiley face isn't yet there.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:23.000
That's because this piece of content, usually by default,

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:25.000
it's only going to check every like 15 minutes

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:28.000
to see if there's a change to that GitHub repository.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.000
So we could just hang out here for 15 minutes

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.000
and wait for that change to take effect.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:36.000
And this is a timeframe that can be modified

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:37.000
by your system administrators.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:40.000
But we can actually just manually kick off that check.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:44.000
So if I go to my info tab here, scroll down,

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:48.000
check for updates periodically for that GitHub repository,

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:51.000
or I can just have it manually check and click update now.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:53.000
So let's go ahead and click this button.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:57.000
So it says changes were found in the Git repository,

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:59.000
so it automatically rebuilds it.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:00.000
Hit okay.

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:04.000
And now you can see the smiley face reflected here

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:07.000
in our final Shiny application.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:10.000
So again, GitPack deployment is a fantastic way

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:13.000
for collaborating with others

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:16.000
and also having a piece of content hosted on Connect

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:20.000
that's automatically updated anytime someone makes a change

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:23.000
to that branch on the GitHub repository.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:29.000
And that wraps up our last PositConnect.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:33.000
That wraps up our last PositTeam workflow of 2023.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:35.000
And I really hope you all found today's session helpful

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:38.000
for collaborative data science.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:40.000
Now, usually for these sessions,

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:43.000
we'd have a live question and answer right afterwards.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.000
But just given the time of the year

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:48.000
and the fact that a lot of people are out of the office,

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:49.000
we instead wanted to provide you

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:51.000
with another way to ask questions.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.000
So on the screen here will be a link to a forum

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.000
on Posit's community page,

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:59.000
which we'd welcome any questions about today's content.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.000
Finally, as a reminder,

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:04.000
all of these PositTeam demos are recorded

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:07.000
and publicly available, which you can view on YouTube.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:09.000
We hope you have a great holiday season,

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:11.000
and we look forward to seeing you again

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:14.000
for our next workflow in 2024.

